    value: 憖
english:
  title: 'Funeral Oration for Minister Kim Sang-seo: A Preface Delivered in Place of the Son-in-law'
  author: Lim Chun
  language: eng
  text: 'I reflect upon the departed spirit: exalted in bearing, majestic in virtue—like the phoenix and the qilin, like stars and clouds, an early omen of fortune for the court. Like jade and precious vessels, like gold and tin, a sublime embodiment of noble character. Long did such a spirit harbor the lofty ambitions of governance, yet never ascended to the highest office. Alas, in this age came the calamity of threefold emptiness, and Heaven showed mercy to no elder. The boat drifted to the abyss; the sword fell in the human world. The tainted blood of Xi Kang moved the Emperor to preserve his memory, yet the lingering grievances of Xiao Taibao became sources of contention for generations. Scholars lost their model, and all who understood could not help but sigh. Woe and sorrow! The reasons for long life and short life perplex both ancients and moderns. Yan Hui was virtuous yet did not live long; Daozhi was wicked yet lived his years. Who can fathom Heaven''s measure of fortune? The rise and fall of the Way rests upon Fate—what more is there to say? How much more so in this declining age when misfortune has befallen such an exceptional man? Woe and sorrow! In his nature and throughout his life, the gentleman was truly different from common men. In the midst of honor and adversity, danger and peril, he remained serene and unmoved, never allowing such trials to mar his countenance. Understanding his destiny, he harbored no anxiety; forgetting himself, he endured all hardship. As fragrant herbs and foul weeds cannot share the same vessel, so the worthy cannot dwell with the base. Yet when jade and stone are burned together in flame, alas, that sage and fool alike turn to ash. Pondering this sorrowful truth, how can the heart not ache? I, though unworthy and of meager talent, have had the honor to become a relation through marriage. Though my abilities pale before Wang Xizhi, I have devoted myself to studying the works of Han Yu, and my heart aspires to emulate Li Han. I humbly present this libation of pure wine; may you receive my sincerest reverence.'
  footnotes:
    - 'The ''threefold emptiness'' (三空) refers to: emptiness of the fields, emptiness of the court, and emptiness of the granaries—a sign of calamity and decline.'
    - Xi Kang and Xiao Taibao were historical figures from Chinese antiquity whose tragic fates serve as precedents for the deceased's own misfortune.
    - The allusions to Wang Xizhi and Han Yu establish the speaker's humble self-assessment while claiming kinship with great literary traditions.
    - This funeral oration combines Confucian reflection on fate and virtue with Daoist acceptance of natural decline, expressing both sorrow and philosophical resignation.
